Ah, you've found yourself in Vim (or Vi), which is a classic "rite of passage" for every developer. It‚Äôs a powerful text editor, but it‚Äôs notoriously confusing to exit if you don't know the secret handshake.

The -- INSERT -- at the bottom of your screen means you are in "Insert Mode," where you can type text. To save and quit, you need to get back to "Command Mode."

How to Save and Quit (The wq command)

  1. Press the Esc key on your keyboard. You‚Äôll notice the -- INSERT -- text at the bottom disappears. You are now back in Command Mode.

  2. Type a colon : (hold Shift + ;). You will see a colon appear at the very bottom left of your screen.

  3. Type wq immediately after the colon (so it looks like :wq).

    • w stands for write (save).

    • q stands for quit.

  4. Press Enter.

What if you just want to get out without saving?

If you accidentally typed something and just want to escape:

  1. Press Esc.

  2. Type :q! and press Enter. This tells the computer to "Quit and ignore any changes I made."

Step 1: The Code

We need to update your app.py to handle the new requirements (Title, Contents, Completed, CreatedAt, UpdatedAt).

Action: Delete everything currently in your app.py and paste this entire block of code. This is the complete, working version for Phase 1.

Python
from flask import Flask, jsonify, request
from datetime import datetime

app = Flask(__name__)

# This is our temporary database
DATA = {
    "items": []
}

def get_next_id():
    # If list is empty, start at ID 1. Otherwise, find the highest ID and add 1.
    if not DATA["items"]:
        return 1
    return max(item["id"] for item in DATA["items"]) + 1

@app.route("/")
def index():
    return "Your To-Do API is running!"

# --- CREATE (The 'C' in CRUD) ---
@app.route("/items", methods=["POST"])
def create_item():
    data = request.get_json()
    
    # Validation: Make sure they sent a title
    if not data or "title" not in data:
        return jsonify({"error": "Title is required"}), 400

    # Get the current time
    current_time = datetime.now().isoformat()

    new_item = {
        "id": get_next_id(),
        "title": data["title"],
        "contents": data.get("contents", ""), # Defaults to empty string if missing
        "completed": False,                   # Always starts as False
        "createdAt": current_time,
        "updatedAt": current_time
    }
    
    DATA["items"].append(new_item)
    return jsonify(new_item), 201

# --- READ (The 'R' in CRUD) ---
@app.route("/items", methods=["GET"])
def list_items():
    return jsonify(DATA["items"])

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(port=8000, debug=True)

  2. In your terminal (inside the CODING folder), run:

This is the "U" in CRUD. It‚Äôs slightly smarter than the others because it needs to:

  1. Find the specific item by its ID.

  2. Change only what you tell it to (like marking it "completed").

  3. Crucially: Update the updatedAt timestamp automatically (so you know when it changed).

Step 1: The Code

Copy this entire block and paste it at the bottom of your app.py (but above the if __name__ == "__main__": line).

Python
# --- UPDATE (The 'U' in CRUD) ---
@app.route("/items/<int:item_id>", methods=["PUT"])
def update_item(item_id):
    # 1. Find the item
    item = next((i for i in DATA["items"] if i["id"] == item_id), None)
    
    # 2. If it doesn't exist, yell at the user
    if item is None:
        return jsonify({"error": "Item not found"}), 404

    # 3. Get the new data
    data = request.get_json()

    # 4. Update fields ONLY if the user sent them
    if "title" in data:
        item["title"] = data["title"]
    if "contents" in data:
        item["contents"] = data["contents"]
    if "priority" in data:
        item["priority"] = data["priority"]
    if "completed" in data:
        item["completed"] = data["completed"]

    # 5. Always update the timestamp
    item["updatedAt"] = datetime.now().isoformat()

    return jsonify(item)

Step 1: The Code (Delete)

Add this block to the bottom of app.py (before if __name__...).

This code is ruthless. It finds the item by ID and removes it from the list forever.

# --- DELETE (The 'D' in CRUD) ---
@app.route("/items/<int:item_id>", methods=["DELETE"])
def delete_item(item_id):
    global DATA
    # This weird looking line keeps every item EXCEPT the one we want to delete
    DATA["items"] = [item for item in DATA["items"] if item["id"] != item_id]
    
    return jsonify({"message": "Item deleted"}), 200

Your friend asked for a feature to "Delete all todo list items that are completed". This is a very common feature (often called "Cleanup").

# --- CLEANUP (Delete all completed) ---
@app.route("/items/cleanup", methods=["DELETE"])
def cleanup_completed():
    global DATA
    # Logic: Keep the item ONLY if 'completed' is False
    DATA["items"] = [item for item in DATA["items"] if item["completed"] == False]

The Final Logic Boss: Sorting

To do this, we need Python‚Äôs built-in sorted() function.

  • The Problem: Computers don't know that "2026" is bigger than "2025" automatically when looking at a complex dictionary.

  • The Solution: We give it a "Key" (a hint). We tell it: "Look at the createdAt field."

Add this code to app.py:

Python
# --- SORTING (Advanced Read) ---
@app.route("/items/sorted", methods=["GET"])
def get_sorted_items():
    # 'key=lambda x: ...' is just a fancy way of saying:
    # "For every item 'x', use its 'createdAt' value to decide the order."
    # reverse=True means Descending (Newest first).
    sorted_list = sorted(DATA["items"], key=lambda x: x["createdAt"], reverse=True)
    
    return jsonify(sorted_list)

How to Test It

You have discovered the #1 misconception about Git.

GitHub is NOT like Google Drive or Dropbox. It does not "auto-save" or "sync" in real-time.

Think of it like writing a letter:

  1. Save (Cmd+S): You finished writing the letter on your desk.

  2. Add & Commit: You put the letter in an envelope and sealed it.

  3. Push: You actually walked to the post office and mailed it.

Right now, you have saved the file on your desk, but you haven't mailed it yet.

The "Mail It" Routine

Every time you want your changes to show up on GitHub, you must run these three commands in order.

Type these into your terminal one by one:

Bash
git add .

(This tells Git: "I want to include ALL the file changes I just made.")

Bash
git commit -m "Built the full todo list api"

(This tells Git: "Seal the envelope and label it 'Built the full todo list api'.")

Bash
git push

(This tells Git: "Send it to the cloud!")

How to verify

  1. Wait for the terminal to finish (it will mention main -> main).

  2. Go back to your browser window with GitHub open.

  3. Refresh the page.

Part 2: Fixing the "Vanishing Data" (SQLite)

To stop the janitor from wiping your whiteboard, we need a Filing Cabinet. In Python, this is called SQLite. It saves your data into a real file on your hard drive.

We are going to do this in two steps.

Step A: Create the "Filing Cabinet"

We need to tell Python: "When you start, check if we have a filing cabinet. If not, buy one."

Action:

    Python

Python
def init_db():
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')
    c = conn.cursor()
    c.execute('''
        CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS items (
            id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
            title TEXT NOT NULL,
            contents TEXT,
            priority TEXT,
            completed BOOLEAN,
            created_at TEXT,
            updated_at TEXT
        )
    ''')
    conn.commit()
    conn.close()

Step B: Updating "Create" (The 'C')

Now we need to teach your create_item worker to put the form in the cabinet (database), not on the whiteboard.

Replace your entire create_item function with this:

Python
@app.route("/items", methods=["POST"])
def create_item():
    data = request.get_json()
    
    # 1. Validation (Same as before)
    if not data or "title" not in data:
        return jsonify({"error": "Title is required"}), 400

    current_time = datetime.now().isoformat()
    
    # 2. Connect to the filing cabinet
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')
    c = conn.cursor()
    
    # 3. Insert the data (SQL Language)
    # The '?' marks are placeholders for safety
    c.execute('''
        INSERT INTO items (title, contents, priority, completed, created_at, updated_at)
        VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)
    ''', (
        data["title"],
        data.get("contents", ""),
        data.get("priority", "Medium"),
        False,  # completed is False by default
        current_time,
        current_time
    ))
    
    # 4. Save and Close
    conn.commit()
    new_id = c.lastrowid # Get the ID of the item we just made
    conn.close()

    # Return the new ID so the user knows it worked
    return jsonify({"id": new_id, "message": "Saved to database!"}), 201

@app.route("/items", methods=["GET"])
def list_items():

    # This weird line helps us get data back as a dictionary (key: value)

    c = conn.cursor()
    
    c.execute("SELECT * FROM items")
    rows = c.fetchall()
    
    # Convert database rows back to a Python list
    results = [dict(row) for row in rows]
    
    conn.close()

Step B: The "Create" Worker (Retraining)

We are going to replace your create_item function.

The "Why" (Since you want to learn):

  • Old way: DATA["items"].append(...) (Just adding to a list in RAM).

  • New way: We use SQL (Structured Query Language). It‚Äôs a language used to talk to databases.

    • INSERT INTO items... literally means "Put this data into the 'items' table."

    • VALUES (?, ?...) are placeholders. We put the actual data in separately for security (to prevent hackers from messing with your database).

    • conn.commit() is crucial. It‚Äôs like hitting "Save" in Word. If you don't do this, the data is lost.

    # We use '?' as safety placeholders

        INSERT INTO items (title, contents, priority, completed, created_at, updated_at)

Step D: Updating "Delete" (The 'D')

We need to tell Python: "Go into the filing cabinet, find the folder with this ID, and shred it."

The Code Logic:

  1. Connect to the DB.

  2. Execute the SQL command: DELETE FROM items WHERE id = ?.

    • Critically Important: We must check c.rowcount after. This tells us how many rows were deleted. If it is 0, it means that ID didn't exist.

  3. Commit (Save the change).

Action: Replace your delete_item function with this:

Python
@app.route("/items/<int:item_id>", methods=["DELETE"])
def delete_item(item_id):
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')
    c = conn.cursor()
    
    # The SQL command to destroy
    c.execute("DELETE FROM items WHERE id = ?", (item_id,))
    
    conn.commit()
    
    # Check if we actually deleted anything
    if c.rowcount == 0:
        conn.close()
        return jsonify({"error": "Item not found"}), 404
        
    conn.close()
    return jsonify({"message": "Item deleted"}), 200

The Final Boss: Updating "Update" (The 'U')

This is the hardest one. Why? Because the user might only want to update the "title", but leave "contents" alone.

In SQL, we have to be very specific. We can't just say "update it." We have to say "Update the title to X, but keep everything else."

We are going to use a Dynamic SQL Builder. This is a pro-level technique. We build the query sentence piece by piece based on what the user sent us.

Action: Replace your update_item function with this:

Python
@app.route("/items/<int:item_id>", methods=["PUT"])
def update_item(item_id):
    data = request.get_json()
    
    # 1. Start building the SQL sentence
    # We will collect pieces like "title = ?" and "completed = ?"
    fields_to_update = []
    values = []
    
    if "title" in data:
        fields_to_update.append("title = ?")
        values.append(data["title"])
        
    if "contents" in data:
        fields_to_update.append("contents = ?")
        values.append(data["contents"])
        
    if "priority" in data:
        fields_to_update.append("priority = ?")
        values.append(data["priority"])
        
    if "completed" in data:
        fields_to_update.append("completed = ?")
        values.append(data["completed"])
        
    # If they didn't send any valid fields, stop here
    if not fields_to_update:
        return jsonify({"error": "No data provided"}), 400
        
    # Always update the 'updatedAt' time
    fields_to_update.append("updated_at = ?")
    values.append(datetime.now().isoformat())
    
    # Add the ID at the end for the "WHERE id = ?" part
    values.append(item_id)
    
    # 2. Join the pieces together into one big SQL string
    # It will look like: "UPDATE items SET title = ?, completed = ? WHERE id = ?"
    sql_query = f"UPDATE items SET {', '.join(fields_to_update)} WHERE id = ?"
    
    # 3. Execute it
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')
    c = conn.cursor()
    c.execute(sql_query, values)
    conn.commit()
    
    if c.rowcount == 0:
        conn.close()
        return jsonify({"error": "Item not found"}), 404
        
    conn.close()
    
    # 4. Return the updated item so the user can see it
    return jsonify({"message": "Item updated", "id": item_id})

@app.route("/items/cleanup", methods=["DELETE"])
def cleanup_completed():
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')
    c = conn.cursor()
    
    # SQL: Delete every row where completed is 1 (True)
    c.execute("DELETE FROM items WHERE completed = 1")
    
    conn.commit()

    conn.close()

@app.route("/items/sorted", methods=["GET"])
def get_sorted_items():
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')
    conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row
    c = conn.cursor()
    
    # SQL: Select all items, but order them by creation date (Descending)
    c.execute("SELECT * FROM items ORDER BY created_at DESC")
    rows = c.fetchall()
    
    results = [dict(row) for row in rows]
    conn.close()
    
    return jsonify(results)

@app.route("/items", methods=["GET"])

# --- UPDATE (The 'U' in CRUD) ---

@app.route("/items/<int:item_id>", methods=["PUT"])

def update_item(item_id):

data = request.get_json()

# 1. Start building the SQL sentence

# We will collect pieces like "title = ?" and "completed = ?"

fields_to_update = []

values = []

if "title" in data:

fields_to_update.append("title = ?")

values.append(data["title"])

if "contents" in data:

fields_to_update.append("contents = ?")

values.append(data["contents"])

if "priority" in data:

fields_to_update.append("priority = ?")

values.append(data["priority"])

if "completed" in data:

fields_to_update.append("completed = ?")

values.append(data["completed"])

# If they didn't send any valid fields, stop here

if not fields_to_update:

return jsonify({"error": "No data provided"}), 400

# Always update the 'updatedAt' time

fields_to_update.append("updated_at = ?")

values.append(datetime.now().isoformat())

# Add the ID at the end for the "WHERE id = ?" part

values.append(item_id)

# 2. Join the pieces together into one big SQL string

# It will look like: "UPDATE items SET title = ?, completed = ? WHERE id = ?"

sql_query = f"UPDATE items SET {', '.join(fields_to_update)} WHERE id = ?"

# 3. Execute it

conn = sqlite3.connect('todo.db')

c = conn.cursor()

c.execute(sql_query, values)

conn.commit()

if c.rowcount == 0:

conn.close()

return jsonify({"error": "Item not found"}), 404

conn.close()

# 4. Return the updated item so the user can see it

return jsonify({"message": "Item updated", "id": item_id})


# --- DELETE (The 'D' in CRUD) ---

@app.route("/items/<int:item_id>", methods=["DELETE"])

def delete_item(item_id):

conn.commit()

# Check if we actually deleted something (rowcount tells us how many rows were affected)

Python
import sqlite3

DB_NAME = "todo.db"

def get_db_connection():
    """Opens a connection to the database and returns it."""
    conn = sqlite3.connect(DB_NAME)
    conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row # This lets us access columns by name
    return conn

def init_db():
    """Creates the tables if they don't exist."""
    conn = get_db_connection()
    c = conn.cursor()
    c.execute('''
        CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS items (
            id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
            title TEXT NOT NULL,
            contents TEXT,
            priority TEXT,
            completed BOOLEAN,
            created_at TEXT,
            updated_at TEXT
        )
    ''')
    conn.commit()
    conn.close()

Your code works and is tested, but it's "messy" because everything (database logic, server settings, routes) is stuffed into one file. If you add User Login now, app.py will become a nightmare to read.

Let's become an Architect. We are going to split your code into specialized files.

Step 1: The "Database Manager" (db.py)

We will move all the "plumbing" (connecting to SQLite) out of your main application and into a dedicated file.

  1. Create a new file named db.py.

  2. Paste this code into it:

Python
import sqlite3

# This separates the config from the code
DB_NAME = "todo.db"

def get_db_connection():
    """Establishes a connection to the database."""
    conn = sqlite3.connect(DB_NAME)
    conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row  # Allows accessing columns by name (row['title'])
    return conn

def init_db():
    """Creates the table if it doesn't exist."""
    conn = get_db_connection()
    with conn:
        conn.execute('''
            CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS items (
                id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
                title TEXT NOT NULL,
                contents TEXT,
                priority TEXT,
                completed BOOLEAN,
                created_at TEXT,
                updated_at TEXT
            )
        ''')
    conn.close()

Step 2: Clean up the Main App (app.py)

Now we strip app.py down so it only handles Routes (URLs). It shouldn't worry about how to connect to the database, it should just ask db.py for a connection.

Open app.py and make these changes:

  1. Imports:

    • Remove: import sqlite3 (You won't need it directly anymore).

    • Add: from db import get_db_connection, init_db.

  2. Remove Old Setup:

    • Delete the DB_NAME = "todo.db" line (it's in db.py now).

    • Delete the old init_db() function definition.

  3. Update the Connection Logic:

    • Find every line that says conn = sqlite3.connect(...).

    • Replace it with: conn = get_db_connection().

    • (You also don't need conn.row_factory = ... anymore, because get_db_connection handles it).

  4. Initialize:

    • Make sure you still call init_db() once near the top of the file (after creating app = Flask...).

Step 3: The "Sanity Check"

Bash
pytest
